{"key":"post-12430763","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12430763</id>\n<content>Plants have been tried hundreds, if not thousands of times by members here.&amp;nbsp; First of all, they don't absorb nearly enough CO2 to be of benefit. You'd need a whole greenhouse of plants to consume the CO2 from an indoor grow.&amp;nbsp; Second and most important, is they don't survive well in a high humidity environment.&amp;nbsp; You'll get cobweb mold and trichoderma in the plant soil, which will then spread to the mushroom project.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Mini-greenhouses don't generally work too well for cakes, which prefer 99% humidity AND fresh air exchange.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12430787</next>\n<prev>12430313</prev>\n<first>12429925</first>\n<last>12517775</last>\n<when>1271861138</when>\n<utime>04/21/10 05:45 PM</utime>\n</post>"}